<br>
You crack me up!  Thanks for the nice compliments.  You were doing very well on Saturday, for sure.  You'll catch plenty of fish with the casting you are doing.  If I can re-emphasize one point, it's to try to PULL THE LINE INTO MOTION.  If your acceleration doesn't begin before the rod reaches the 12:00 position, then you have to cram an entire acceleration stroke into a very short distance.  It brings on the tailing loops as you get more and more line out.<br>
<br>
Yes, I am definitely more accurate and comfortable overall when I am hauling.  It is not just about increasing line speed to me.  It's about overall control of the system.  Having two hands sharing the work allows better refinement of the mechanics.  The smoothness and grace is achieved by eliminating as close to 100% of the slack as you can achieve.  Hauling helps me to do that.  And since you are doing a significant portion of the work with the line hand, the rod hand will not get as tired as it would without a haul.<br>
<br>
Now I will admit, when I am casting very short, like under 20', I don't haul all the time.   Especially when I am tuck casting and high-sticking.  Then, I typically have my left hand on the wading staff, and my right hand is the only hand fishing.  <br>
<br>
My haul definitely has as many styles and intensities as my casting stroke with the rod.  Maybe more, in fact.  With a tiny dry fly that I need to flick sharply under an overhanging tree, my haul would be very short and sharp.  When I lob a big bass popper onto a glassy smooth surface, my haul is very long, but slow.  Just like the casting stroke I'm making with the rod.<br>
<br>
When I'm out in the bays in winter, blind casting the guts, I like to cast as far as I can.  The further you cast, the fewer times you have to.  And the more time the fly is in the water with the fish.  In this case, I start in a half-squat, leaning forward on my left foot, and the rod tip is in the water.  I aggressively accelerate the rod from this position to my final stopping position, about 180 degrees of total stroke.  80% of my weight has shifted to my back (right) foot.  And of course, there's a haul mixed in, and it's vicious.  My intention is to get that 60 feet of line SMOKIN, so I can shoot about 15 or 20 feet into the backcast.  Then when it's unrolled behind, a similar agressive forward stroke to launch the remainder of the line.  If I can get from 60 feet to 100 feet in a single pick up and lay down, I'm happy.  False casting in the wind is futile.<br>
<br>
As described in that previous paragraph, my casting stroke is very tight and controlled.  I think and concentrate very hard on making the tip move in the absolute straightest line that I can, right up to the stop.  It's easier to hold it all together with a single pickup and lay down.  But it's a lot like work, and not the relaxing &quot;zen&quot; kind of casting that most people crave.  Sure is effective for the purpose, though...<br>
<br>
I don't know much about women, ask my wife.  I don't think I could write a book about teaching them much of anything....  Just kidding, of course.  In many ways, it's easier to teach women and children, than to teach men that have been fishing all their lives with other types of tackle.  Ladies and kids listen better than we do....  And they don't have that darned baitcaster's wrist flick....<br>
<br>
Are you coming to the Sunfish Spectacular down at Seven Lakes this weekend, John?  We're gonna have our last casting class right after the BBQ.  We are also having a casting carnival before the BBQ that will be lots of fun.  Accuracy, loop control, distance.  Kinda like an obstacle course with a flyrod.  And of course, we'll have prizes for the longest cast, most consecutive casts in the hoola hoop, etc.  Let me know if you need directions.<br>
<br>
