 Hauling is nothing more than Total Line control.<br>
 The single haul going backward or backcasting is the easiest. Your hands are moving apart. ON the front cast your hands are coming together. So you have to get the line hand moving a little faster. <br>
 Now to gain more control how about a third haul.<br>
 Lets say you want to cast around a stump.<br>
 right sidearm cast. little haul on the back cast to help load the backcast. A other haul on the front cast to increase the line speed. Now just as the line is straighting out. Give the third haul and watch the last 6 feet of line come around the stump in a nice left hook.<br>
 How about a Tuck or dump cast. Starts with a over head cast. increase the line speed. Aim a little high.<br>
 Give a Third haul as the line straightens. Watch the fly drop down under the loop and settle on the water.<br>
  These are all hauls the hauls are used to increase the line speed to almost over loading the rod and causing the kick back to help place your fly.<br>
 Like I said in the beginning Hauls are for line control. If your rod is loading you can control the line better. <br>
 As once was said I forget who. &quot;Line Speed line speed line speed.&quot;<br>
  ol Al <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chofujohn@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>chofujohn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#000000>(5/5/03 2:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Line control, eh?</span><hr size=1> Hi FlySoup,<br>
